snippet.textDisplay: It’s normal during these times to argue, just take it easy on your wife as becoming a mother is extremely stressful and has an impact on her in ways a man can never understand or feel. Just don’t shout at her, never insult or degrade each other & you will see how these tough times will pass. Having a baby is not easy and the recovery from having a baby both physical and psychological can take over a year post partum. Be careful whilst arguing with the mother of your daughter in front of your daughter as you are showing her how a man should treat her, very very important you set an example of respect, empathy and care for her mother so she will be able to pick a man that will support not make her life hell. Best of luck. Me and my husband been through it with our first our son & I promise you when you learn to grow up and not let passive aggression induce a unhealthy reaction out of you it’ll be calmmmmm. Just remember every time you shout to or around your child it alters the structure of their brain permanently and can damage them in ways we’ll never know. So just think of your child first and you think about giving her a good chance at life by not effin her up in head. I say this from experience so please try to understand a nuclear family is better than a broken distant one so try not to give up too early.

snippet.textDisplay: Separation isn’t divorce and it shouldn’t be thought of as an end to marriage. Seperation is when two people give each other space and have time to reflect on things and focus on themselves for a while. I understand you and Amna have given each other space and time but sometimes you need to be given space and time through seperating and then if you come back and things still aren’t settling for a while, that’s when you should think about divorce, because just as you said marriage isn’t a joke especially if u have a kid involved. Also, time apart from your partner could make you appreciate them more and realise the importance of them in your life, which will make you reluctant to argue about petty things with them and more willing to compromise.
